match.name: November NRL22 Monthly COF
match.about:
Exciting, Challenging and Fun!
Anyone can participate!

We welcome shooters of all skill levels from first time beginners to experienced competitors, including women shooters, Air Rifles, Old Guns, and especially Young Guns. No matter your age or skill level, you will have fun and make memories to last a lifetime.  This is the perfect way to get introduced to the world of competitive shooting.  The NRL22 specializes in first time competitors and is welcoming to everyone at any skill level.

This match will be the official NRL22 November Course Of Fire (COF).  We will run the 5 NRL22 stages plus a couple bonus stages depending on attendance.  If you need any information on this match or the NRL22 organization, you can find it on our website www.saltlakenrl22.com or at www.nrl22.com

Hope to see you at the range!
match.waiver:
By attending our match,
you agree to always abide by the following rules!

Welcome shooters!
The Salt Lake, Big Salty NRL22 Club is a fun event designed around a family & friend style atmosphere.  We embrace a comfortable friendly competitive match with a primary focus on safety.   The Big Salty range is owned by the UDWR, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources and is offered for the use of private clubs to host competitive matches in Salt Lake City.  For us to continue to have this facility for our use and for the safety of our competitors and guests, the following rules must be followed.
The 4 rules of firearms safety
1.	Treat every firearm as loaded, even unloaded ones!
2.	Never point your weapon at anything you are not willing to kill or destroy!
3.	Never put your finger on the trigger until you are on target and ready to fire!
4.	Always know what your target is and what is behind it!
Salt Lake, Big Salty NRL22 Range Rules
1.	Salt Lake NRL22 operates a “Cold Range”.  Rifles can only be loaded on the firing line and only at the direction of the Range or Squad Officer of each squad.  All shooters must unload and make safe their rifle before removing their rifle from the firing line.  At no other time during the entire event is your magazine (empty or loaded) allowed to be inserted into your rifle.
2.	The Salt Lake NRL22 observes the “180 rule” while on the firing line. At no time during a stage, can the muzzle of your rifle break 180 degrees of the firing line.  Parents must assist their Young Gun shooters with this rule, especially when transitioning shooting positions. For new shooters, the “muzzle” is the end of your rifle (barrel).  If you do not understand the “180 rule”, please ask a range officer or match director before the match starts.
3.	IF YOU MUZZLE ANYONE AT ANY TIME, REGARDLESS OF CIRCUMSTANCE, YOU WILL BE IMMEDIATELY DISQUALIFIED, YOU WLL PUT YOUR RIFLE AND GEAR AWAY AND MUST LEAVE THE RANGE.  THIS IS YOUR ONLY WARNING; VIOLATION OF THIS RULE IS ABSOLUTE.  It is the responsibility of the competitor to maintain control of your rifle at all times.   There are no exceptions to this rule!
4.	All rifles must have MAGAZINE OUT and BOLT OPEN at all times unless on the firing line to start the stage.  Semi-auto rifles must have MAGAZINE OUT, BOLT LOCKED BACK, and SAFETY ENGAGED.  Chamber flags are required when removing your rifle from the firing line and when the rifle is stored.  A colored zip tie or plastic weed eater line works great as a chamber flag.  If you do not have a chamber flag, the match director can provide one for you at no cost.
5.	All firearms must be stored in a rack with muzzle up or on the ground pointed downrange or in a marked designated area pointing towards one of the shooting berms.
6.	When relocating or moving your rifle while outside of a rifle case, your rifle must be held in a direct upright position with muzzle above your head.
7.	No repairs or service is to be done to any firearms in the area that the match is being conducted.  During repairs, you are 100% responsible for your rifle’s muzzle and the same rules apply (see #3 above). You must notify the match director before doing any repairs on any firearms.
8.	If a cold range or cease fire is called for any reason, all shooters must immediately make their firearms safe by removing mags, opening bolts and moving away from your rifles (semi-auto’s must remove mag and lock bolt back).   Firearms will remain in place where they are.  If your firearm is not in a stable safe position, you must immediately move it to the nearest stable position and move away. You are not allowed to touch your firearms during this time until instructed by the Match Director or Range Officer.
9.	Non-prescription drugs and/or alcohol are NEVER allowed on the range property.  Any competitor that is assumed to be intoxicated or under any influence will be asked to leave the range.  If you are intoxicated or under the influence, you will not be allowed to drive.
10.	Good sportsmanship is a major part of our sport.  This includes being respectful to all competitors, guests, range officers, and match directors not only in competitive nature, but also with language and gestures.  We encourage ladies, families, and young guns to our matches and not everybody can tolerate cursing, vulgar or suggestive talk.  Good sportsmanship also includes fairness in all things.  Cheating is not tolerated.  Cheating includes trying to “game” a stage in a way that gives a competitor an unfair advantage over others.  If you have a question on how a stage “can” be shot, ask for clarification from the match director before shooting to make sure you are not gaming the stage.  Stages are designed to be shot in the “Spirit in which it was created” and the instructions/descriptions may not include every possible way the stage “could” be shot.
11.	The match director has the final say in any dispute without argument or disruption.
12.	Be safe and have fun.  The Big Salty Range is a scarce resource this close to the city.  Please respect it by keeping it clean, inviting your friends, and following all rules. 
If you are in violation of any rule, whether intentionally or unintentionally, you agree to accept the consequences and penalties given by the Match Director and/or Range Officer without confrontation or conflict.  The Match Director has final say in all disputes. 

Salt Lake, Big Salty NRL22
